<br>
I never knew my birth-father.  If my foster mother knew, she surely would have told me.  Aye.  I was fostered.  At a very young age.  As a babe, I am told.<br>
<br>
My foster parents are human merchants in the City of Freeport.  Da sells arms.  Swords, pikes, daggers and such.  He is an excellent blacksmith and craftsmen.  Ma works in leather.  She makes leather jerkins, scabbards, quivers.  Mostly complementing Da’s wares.<br>
<br>
I learned the art of swordsmanship from Da at a young age.  Demonstrating the quality of his swords for customers who were often amused to see a young half-elven child trying to heft a sword almost as large as she was.<br>
<br>
Ma had a high-elven friend.  Or so I thought anyway.  I was in awe of her.  So tall and pretty!  I used to hide behind Ma’s skirts and peek out at her when she came to visit.  She would bring me the best presents.  Gifts of toys, sweetmeats and clothing.  I would always be lured out from behind Ma’s skirts and sit, bouncing on her knees, getting my grubby little hands on her robes, playing with the necklaces she wore.<br>
<br>
It was much later that Ma told me that she was my birth-mother.  When I was old enough to understand, I guess.  Maybe I wasn’t.  Because as I recall, I was real nasty to her the next time she visited.  Ma was pretty mad at me, and I guess I upset my birth-mother a lot, because I seldom saw her again after that, but the gifts continued coming.  Sent by messenger, and I still accepted them.  Like Da would say, to Ma.  “Waste not, want not.  Let Lainie keep them.  Afterall… why not?  What would we do with them?  Return everything and hurt her even further?”  Yes, I eavesdropped unashamedly when they talked about me and my birth-mother.  I wanted to learn all I could about her, but never knew how to ask.<br>
<br>
Ma must have continued to send my birth-mother periodic reports.  For the presents that came to me suited each step in my life.  Shurikens when I was learning to throw.  Jewelry to enhance my strength when I chose the way of the warrior.  Pieces of magical armor when I began to grow out of my leather, blackened iron greaves when I complained that leather didn’t cover much of my bottom.<br>
<br>
Ma made me send polite notes of thanks each time, and finally, one day I decided to visit Felwithe.  To learn more of my birth-mother’s home.  I thought perhaps, like all children like to fantasize, that my birth-mother was a Princess.  My birth-father her forbidden love.  Probably a Prince of Qeynos or some such.<br>
<br>
I ended up surprising my mother’s mother.  The grandmother I never knew I had.  She welcomed me with open arms and fussed more than I would have liked.  But she was a kind woman.  Young in the way high-elves were.  They never aged, it seemed, to my eyes.  I realized, that visit, how important my mother’s family was.  Grandmother was Seer to the Royal family of Felwithe.  I also found that I had an aunt, called to Tunare (whatever that meant) and a half-elven uncle who was a bard.  Seemed that my grand-da sowed some wild oats in his time.  I gathered from what my grandma told me, that my birth father was a Cleric of Marr.  He was probably a high-ranking fellow at the Temple.  Who knows? Maybe a high-ranking priest.  But, she would not tell me his name either.  <br>
<br>
“That is for your mother to tell you.  Make your peace with her.”<br>
<br>
I still remember her words clearly.  She was firm and would not be swayed.  ‘Fact, she got angry and scolded me when I tried to press her for more information but she gifted me with a heavy pouch of coin and bade me write and visit.<br>
<br>
That visit to Felwithe also made me realize how lucky I was that my birth mother had decided to foster me in Freeport.  Freeport is a bustling seaport with people from all over Norrath living there.  Half-elves, humans and high-elves were the most common, even though there were also gnomes, dwarves, halflings and the occasional erudite.  I grew up without prejudice shown me.  But in Felwithe, where everything was shiningly clean and elegant, I received short shrift from the high-elven merchants and sneers from town-folk when I asked directions.<br>
<br>
Upon my return to Freeport, I made my decisions.  I had chosen the way of the warrior early in my life.  Now I chose to follow Mithaniel Marr.  God of Valor.  May I one day bring pride to my name and my family.  Both my foster family and my birth family.<br>
<br>
Perhaps if I am worthy, my birth mother will accept me with pride, and my birth father would recognize me as his daughter.<br>
