        <br>
With an inward sigh, she continued her embroidery.  She had not dwelled upon her lost love in a long while, and she was not about to do so now.<br>
<br>
Delaine completed the cleaning and oiling of her much prized weapons and sheathed them carefully.  Putting them down, she stood to dispose of the cleaning rags.  She smiled at the picture her mother and grandmother made.  Drinking tea, doing embroidery.  So dainty and refined.  How did she come about?  She grinned.  Probably from her father.  She was shorter, stockier… after all, her father was human.<br>
<br>
Hmmm… this might be the right time to broach the subject again.  She approached the table.  Her grandmother smiled and offered her tea.  She sat down and accepted.<br>
<br>
So.  Delaine wanted to talk.  Cassandra knew this day would come.  She decided to open the conversational sallies.  “So, have you decided on a surname yet, my dear?  You are close to it now.  That is… if you wish to take a last name?”  Cassandra raised a delicate eyebrow.<br>
<br>
Delaine grinned.  “Well, Gramma, I’m not sure.  You know, I always thought I’d pick a name close to my mother’s or my father’s.  But I don’t know my father’s name.”<br>
<br>
Arawyne put down her embroidery and poured herself a cup of tea.  It was time.  Definitely time.  Taking a sip, she regarded her daughter solemnly.  Delaine watched her with a mixture of wariness and eagerness.  Arawyne set the fine china cup down.  It clinked softly on the saucer.  Picking up a napkin, she dabbed her lips.<br>
