<br>
“Bravo.  Very insightful of you, Arawyne.  Do not tease the child if you do not wish to tell her about him yourself.”<br>
<br>
Arawyne had the grace to look ashamed.  Her heart was wrung painfully, and she had not thought it would hurt so badly after all this time.  She smiled a wry smile at her daughter.  Her mother was right.<br>
<br>
“What is it that you wish to know, Lainie?  Ask and I shall try my best to answer you.”<br>
<br>
Delaine looked at her grandmother gratefully and then the questions spilled out eagerly.  One following the other more and more easily.<br>
<br>
~~~<br>
<br>
Arawyne was exhausted.  After the emotional grilling she had put herself through answering her daughter’s questions about the man she once loved more than life itself, she had taken her own leave of her mother and fled to Rivervale. One of the few cities in which she had not spent time with Dalain, and hence one that did not bring back memories too painful to consider.  She sat on the hillside opposite the bank.  It had always been a favorite spot for her.  As dusk fell, light spilled from the windows and the shadows grew longer until darkness wrapped the city in a blanket of night.<br>
<br>
