<br>
Turning it over, he looked at the unfamiliar script on the envelope and frowned.  Who would be writing him?  It had been many, many years since he used to receive letters on a regular basis.  Indeed he could not remember the last time he received one.  He had no living relatives.  Once… once, he had a lover.  But that was long years past.<br>
<br>
Walking back to his rooms, he placed the mail on his desk.  The envelope lay, glaringly out of place among the scrolls and reports.  He decided to open it first.  Tearing it open, he unfolded the single sheet of plain vellum.<br>
<br>
“Dear sir,<br>
<br>
I am but a humble warrior of Marr, but would like to meet you, if you have the time, I would be honored to buy you a drink at the Jade Tiger Inn.<br>
<br>
Delaine <br>
Warrior of Freeport”<br>
<br>
Dalain looked at the letterhead.  Steel Warriors.  What did a warrior maid want of him?  It was dated today, and he wondered if she knew he had just arrived the night before.  He looked at the sun that was still high in the sky and then at the unread reports and scrolls.  Curiosity overcame him and on impulse, he decided to walk to the Arena.  He would learn more of the warrior there in the guild of the Steel Warriors.  He would just have to avoid the guards.  Something he learned to do early in his career as a cleric in the service of Marr.<br>
