<br>
The rhythmic tink-ka-tink of a hammer against steel floated through the air, as did the acrid smell of a smithy’s furnace, inter-mingled with the salt air of the harbor beyond as Dalain walked through the town.  The public furnace was free.  Rather unusual for the time of day, Dalain mused as he opened the door and walked into the blacksmith’s.<br>
<br>
Tislyn looked up at the tinkle of bells as the door to her shop opened, then shook her head bemusedly.  There was no one there.  She turned back to her task and continued stacking molds on the shelf.<br>
<br>
“Mistress Tislyn.”<br>
<br>
“Eek!”<br>
<br>
