<br>
“Well met, good smith.”<br>
<br>
The blacksmith smiled in return and shook his hand, testing the mettle of his visitor.  Dalain strove not to wince at the test of strength in the man’s grip but offered a firm grip in return.<br>
<br>
“Ashord, this is Lord Guerrisant, come to visit our humble abode.”<br>
<br>
“Nay, Mistress Tislyn, no honorifics, please.  I am but a simple cleric of Marr.”<br>
<br>
Ashord grinned and released Dalain’s hand.<br>
<br>
“Ashord Marner, and my wife Tislyn.  Have you come to purchase a blade perhaps?  Or is it other business you have come about?  I have recently tried a new technique to create a functional blade, but one that imparts much beauty to the metal.”<br>
<br>
He picked up the blade that he had been working on and showed it to Dalain.  Dalain examined it closely.  It was certainly different, and quite beautiful.  There were waves and swirls in the blade, yet it was smooth.  He could not feel the lines as he ran his fingers over it, yet they were there.  He turned it over in his hands to admire the handiwork, nodding approvingly.<br>
<br>
Ashord grinned proudly.<br>
<br>
“Much work goes into it.  The metal is folded again and again to create those swirls you see.  It makes an excellent blade and holds a fine edge.  Unfortunately, I can only make so many of them, and few can afford them.  This is elven work.  I was lucky enough that an elven smith divulged the secret to me over ale one eve.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dalain nodded and handed the weapon back to the smith.<br>
<br>
“It certainly is beautiful.”<br>
<br>
Tislyn had left the men as they talked and now returned with a pitcher of ale and fresh muffins.<br>
<br>
“Some refreshment perhaps?”<br>
<br>
She asked as she approached with the laden tray.<br>
<br>
Dalain smiled and reached out both hands to help her, but she lifted it out of his reach.<br>
<br>
“Sit!  Sit!”<br>
<br>
She bade both men and motioned them to the table and bench.  Dalain enjoyed the simple hospitality of Ashord and Tislyn, catching up with the gossip of the city, wondering all the while how he would bring up the subject of Delaine when Ashord asked.<br>
<br>
“Now what can two simple merchants do for you?  It’s not everyday that a High Priest of Marr dodges the Militia to visit and break bread with us.”<br>
<br>
Dalain was silent a moment.<br>
<br>
“A half-elven warrior maid by name of Delaine sought me out today.”<br>
<br>
He replied.<br>
<br>
“I understand she is your daughter?”<br>
<br>
Ashord looked at Dalain warily.<br>
<br>
“Aye.  She is.  A little scamp she is.  She has not insulted you has she?”<br>
<br>
Ashord turned toward the shop and bellowed.<br>
<br>
“Delaine!  Lainie girl!  Come here!”<br>
<br>
“Shush, Ashord!  You treat her like she is a child.  She is a young woman now.”<br>
<br>
Ashord looked at his wife sternly.<br>
<br>
“A young woman who should respect her elders.”<br>
<br>
Dalain grinned.<br>
<br>
“Nay.  She gave me no insult, but left me questions when we met.  She said a few things and then bolted, arousing my curiosity.”<br>
<br>
“Delaine!”<br>
<br>
Ashord bellowed again.<br>
<br>
“What, Da?”<br>
<br>
A feminine voice bellowed back from the upper floor.<br>
<br>
“I said to come out here!  Now!”<br>
<br>
“Coming!  Coming!”<br>
